<TITLE> Obama proposes bank bailout fee </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WASHINGTON, (bdnews24.com/Reuters)---US President Barack Obama is proposing major US financial firms pay a fee to protect taxpayers from up to $117 billion in bailout losses. Amid mounting public anger over multi-million dollar bank bonuses and a multi-billion taxpayer-funded bank bailout, President Barack Obama is proposing major US financial firms pay a fee to protect taxpayers from up to $117 billion in bailout losses. SOUNDBITE: US President Barack Obama saying (English): "My commitment is to recover every single dime the American people are owed. And my determination to achieve this goal is only heightened when I see reports of massive profits and obscene bonuses at the very firms who owe their continued existence to the American people." The levy will recoup losses from the $700 billion taxpayer rescue of US banks called the TARP -- the Troubled Asset Relief Program, that was implemented in 2008 at the height of the global financial panic. SOUNDBITE: US President Barack Obama saying (English): "If these companies are in good enough shape to afford massive bonuses, they are surely in good enough shape to afford paying back every penny to taxpayers." By imposing a fee on big firms with assets of more than $50 billion, the Obama administration expects to raise $90 billion over the first 10 years. Banks that have already repaid TARP money will not be spared the fee, nor will firms that received no TARP mo
